===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}

Uncertain. Various theories have been proposed based on the evidence from the bronze inscriptions:
* {{liushu|p}} of folds in cloth ({{zh-ref|Lin, 1920}});
* {{Han compound|石|乙|ls=psc|c1=s|c2=p|t1=rock}} or {{ltc-l|乀}}. The phonetic component may be replaced with {{och-l|匕|id=1}} (not shown above);
* {{liushu|i}}: half of {{zh-l|*丙|two horses}} – one horse ({{zh-ref|Zhang et al., 1996}}), but the origin of the character {{lang|zh|丙}} is also uncertain (for example, it could be the tail of a fish).

''{{w|Shuowen}}'' considers it to be an {{Han compound|八|匸|ls=ic|ls2=psc|t1=eight|t2=to conceal|c1=p|c2=s|nocap=1}} – unit of measuring cloth. {{zh-l|*八}} refers to eight folds in one {{zh-l|*匹}} of cloth (two bolts of cloth), and {{zh-l|*匸}} refers to concealing the two ends of the cloth when rolling it up. This interpretation is not likely since the older forms evidently do not contain these components.

===Etymology 1===
{{unc|zh}}. Possibly related to {{cog|km|ពីរ||two}} or {{cog|lus|phîr||double; forked; twin}} ({{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}).

{{zh-ref|Wang (1982)}} considers it to be cognate with {{och-l|比|to compare; to match|id=1}}, {{och-l|媲|to match; to pair}}.

The meaning “four zhang of cloth” is probably a special application, but it is reminiscent of {{cog|sit-pro|*pV-lij||four}} ({{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}).

